ForceIn - This policy would logout existing user session and create a new Session (new tokenId)
AttachExisting - This policy would reuse existing user session and Will NOT create a new Session
    User A Login

        connect to web socket [Set-Cookie: JSessionId]
          User A Login (Again without logging out)

                Return the old session. No Password or new Role/Permissions loaded.
                  When Server configured NOT to reissue active session on login
                    Create New Session [Set-Cookie: Authorization: Bearer tokenId, Delete Cookie JSessionId]

                      Same Browser (Different Tab) - User B Login
                        User B login request validated for username/password
                          User A Login JSessionId removed [Set-Cookie: JSessionId=deleted]

true serves when the client is going to automatically disconnect the agent due to inactivity (see {@link #getSessionExpirationInfo}). In this case, most of usual logout restrictions (see {@link #canLogout}) are skipped. However if the agent is assumed as talking by phone, disconnection is prevented anyway by throwing an exception with id = {@link ExceptionCodes#CANNOT_FORCE_LOGOUT_WHEN_TALKING CANNOT_FORCE_LOGOUT_WHEN_TALKING} (code 8). The reason is that an agent on the phone should not be treated as inactive even though they have not been pressing a button on UI for a long time. The agent is assumed as on the phone when there is an active call in {@link CallState#TALKING} state, or a consultant call during warm transfer (i.e. {@link CallInfo#hasIncompleteTransfer} = true), or so on. The client does not necessarily need to check these conditions prior to calling the method. Instead, we recommend just to call it. includeCallerInfo.description:
If you set this option to true, the new call participant receives contact details.
 If you set this option to false or omit, the call participant receives only information
 about you that initiated the call.
 The option should be set to true or omitted if {@link CampaignInfo#flags}

isWarm.description:
Defines if the first conference participant should be added in a warm mode.
 Must be false for the second and next conference participants.

isTransfer.description: Indicates if call is part of transfer activity.

afterCallWorkTimeout.description: After call work timeout. (milliseconds) Not NULL when call is for campaign configured to use it.

campaignId.description:
Campaign Id to which call belongs. This field's value can be used to get campaign specific dispositions for a
 call. It can be null if call is not assigned to any campaign

recording.description:
Indicates if the call is being recorded.
 More exactly, this is what UI should show to the agent about call recording.
 Actually the fact of automatic call recording can be intentionally hidden from the agent.
 In this case, the value of this field is unrelated to real recording.

dispositionId.description: Call disposition. Not NULL when call has been dispositioned.

startTimestamp.description: Time when VCC started processing the call. (Epoch time in milliseconds)

customer.description: Customer title. Not NULL only when state == QUEUED (queued call)

handleTime.description: Total time in milliseconds the call was being handled.

priority.description: Priority of the call. Not NULL only when state == QUEUED (queued call)

hasIncompleteTransfer.description: Indicates that warm transfer is in progress.

isInternalReceiver.description: Indicates if the agent is the receiving part of an internal call.

autoRecording.description:
True if auto recording is configured for the call and this is displayed to the agent. False if either the call is not auto recorded or auto recorded secretly. The agent might stop auto recording, but the field never changes the value during a call. The case when the client needs this value is very rare. Let the agent is on call and the call is being recorded. What if an administrator happens to revoke permission to record calls from the agent at this moment? We recommend the following behavior to the client:
  • If this is manual recording, let the agent stop it if they want.
  • If this is auto recording, do not let the agent stop it.

handleTimestamp.description: Time when an agent started handling the call. (Epoch time in milliseconds)

ivrTransferModule.description: Name of IVR module that transferred the call to the agent.

recordingAllowed.description:
Indicates if the call recording is allowed. UI should not try to toggle recording till it receives websocket
 notification that the call is updated with {@link EventContext#eventReason} =
 {@link CallNotifyReason#RECORDING_ALLOWED RECORDING_ALLOWED}.
 Note that even if the field is true, recording still can be forbidden for other reasons. For example, the agent
 might not have the permission, {@link PermissionEnum#CAN_MAKE_RECORDINGS CAN_MAKE_RECORDINGS}.

addressType.description: Type of call address. Actual for conference call.

parkTime.description: Total time in milliseconds for which the call was in PARKED state.

canRecycle.description: Indicates that call can be recycled what means the recycle disposition can be used to dispose this call.

contactLookupResult.description:
Contact lookup information for the call.

This field can help the agent determine the right {@link #activeContact call contact} when it is not exactly known. A contact can be unknown in case of an inbound call or a manual external call. At the same time, the phone number of the remote party is usually known. VCC tries to match the number with an existent contact in the database. The result of this lookup is placed into the given field. There can be one contact, or multiple contacts, or no contacts at all. {@link #activeContact} is automatically initialized with data of the first contact found (if any). However the agent may choose another contact to associate with the call (see {@link IAgentService#setCallActiveContact}). They can look at the contacts from the given field as the most probable alternatives. At the same time, the agent may select any other contact or create a new one.

stateDuration.description: Duration in milliseconds for which the call is in current state.

isCallback.description: Indicates if the call is a callback

holdTime.description: Total time in milliseconds for which the call was in ON_HOLD state.

holdTimestamp.description: Time when the call entered last ON_HOLD state. (Epoch time in milliseconds)

createTime.description: Time of creating queued call on VCC side. (Epoch time in milliseconds)

stateSince.description: Time when call entered current state. (Epoch time in milliseconds)

transferPauseTimeout.description:
Timeout for transfer (inbound) pause.
 When agent gets a call it may be in state ON_HOLD.
 If transferPauseTimeout > 0 and state == ON_HOLD transfer pause has been applied.
 To calculate left on hold time stateSince and stateDuration may be used.

averageHandleTime.description: Average Handle Time for this type of call. (milliseconds or 0 if not available, e.g. internal calls)

previewId.description: If this is a live call created from preview the field will contain corresponding preview Id. Else null

wrapupTimestamp.description: Time the call entered WRAP_UP state. (Epoch time in milliseconds)

userTransferringId.description: If not null, contains Id of the agent who transferred the call.

parkTimestamp.description: Time when the call entered last PARKED state. (Epoch time in milliseconds)

billingTime.description: Total time in milliseconds for which the call is billed.

talkTime.description: Total time in milliseconds for which the call was in TALKING state.

billingTimestamp.description: Time when billing was started. (Epoch time in milliseconds)

wrapupTime.description: Total time in milliseconds for which the call is/was in WRAP_UP state.

duration.description: Total duration of the call in milliseconds.

acceptTime.description: Time when call was accepted by agent. (Epoch time in milliseconds, 0 until accepted by agent)

talkTimestamp.description: Time when the call entered last TALKING state. (Epoch time in milliseconds)

isAutoAnswer.description:
Indicates if the call is going to be auto-answered. It makes sense only when {@link #state}=
 {@link CallState#OFFERED}. If the field is false, the call can be manually answered or rejected by
 {@link IAgentService#answerCall()} or {@link IAgentService#rejectCall()} respectively.

connectorId.description:

id.description: ID of the pending connector info. Unique for each execution of a connector.

ctiDisplayMode.description: This option should be used by CTI Web UI. Display mode denotes if/how the results of connector execution should be presented to an agent, for example, HTTP request can be executed silently or in a new browser tab.

displayMode.description: This option should be used by regular Web UI Agent. Display mode denotes if/how the results of connector execution should be presented to an agent, for example, HTTP request can be executed silently or in a new browser tab.

checkMultipleContacts.description:
Indicates if a check for multiple contacts should be made. The current sever implementation applies this flag only when making a call. The server ignores the flag when transferring or adding to conference. If the {@link #number number} matches more than one contact and it is not clear what dialing rules to apply, server returns error Q_MULTIPLE_CONTACTS_SELECT(1002). In this case, client should specify the contact explicitly.
UI scenario should be:
  1. set this flag to true, and make the necessary request
  2. if server returns the error, show the list of the matched contacts to let the user choose the right one
  3. if the user selects a contact, apply it to {@link #contactId}; or if the user chooses none, set the flag to false, and contact-specific dialing rules will be ignored
  4. retry the request

skipDNCCheck.description:
Indicates client wants to skip checking if number in DNC list
UI scenario should be:
  1. set this flag to false, and make the necessary request
  2. if server returns an error, do one of the following things according to the error returned:
    NUMBER_IN_DNC_LIST(10006) - show an error dialog;
    Q_NUMBER_IN_DNC_LIST_FORCE(1001) - ask the user for confirmation of the request
  3. if the user confirms, set this flag to true and retry the request
